00:00:12:190000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:00:12:190000.Dialogue: Assuming a device could be invented which would identify the quantum state of matter of an individual in one location and transmit that pattern to a distant location for reassembly, you would not have transported the individual. You would have destroyed him in one location and recreated him in another.

00:00:33:040000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:00:33:040000.Dialogue: Personally, I would never use a transporter, because the original Sheldon would have to be disintegrated in order to create a new Sheldon.

00:00:41:040000.Speaker: Leonard
00:00:41:040000.Dialogue: Would the new Sheldon be in any way an improvement on the old Sheldon?

00:00:46:020000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:00:46:020000.Dialogue: No, he would be exactly the same.

00:00:56:130000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:00:56:130000.Dialogue: Gentlemen, I'd like you to meet Dennis Kim. Dennis is a highly sought-after doctoral candidate, and we're hoping he'll do his graduate work here.

00:01:07:220000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:01:07:220000.Dialogue: Not bad... I, myself, started graduate school at 14.

00:01:11:180000.Speaker: Dennis
00:01:11:180000.Dialogue: Well, I lost a year while my family was tunneling out of North Korea.

00:01:20:230000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:01:20:230000.Dialogue: I thought maybe you boys could show Dennis around. Let him see why we're the best physics research facility in the country.

00:01:26:170000.Speaker: Dennis
00:01:26:170000.Dialogue: I already know you're not. You don't have an Open Science Grid computer or a free electron laser. The string theory research being done here is nothing but a dead end.

00:01:34:130000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:01:34:130000.Dialogue: Excuse me, that is my research, and it is by no means a dead end.

00:01:38:110000.Speaker: Dennis
00:01:38:110000.Dialogue: Obviously you don't see it yet, but trust me, you will.

00:01:43:230000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:01:43:230000.Dialogue: Dennis, we've discussed this. We're in the process of updating our equipment, and we welcome your input on our research goals. We've agreed to look the other way if you use up to 20% of the grant money you attract to smuggle your grandfather out of Pyongyang.

00:01:58:080000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:01:58:080000.Dialogue: We want him here, boys. Make it happen.

00:02:02:120000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:02:02:120000.Dialogue: You can count on us. We're on it. What the hell do you mean, dead end?

00:02:07:020000.Speaker: Dennis
00:02:07:020000.Dialogue: I mean, the whole landscape of false vacuums in string theory could be as large as 10 to the 500th power. In addition... Look, chocolate milk.

00:02:18:060000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:02:18:060000.Dialogue: I sense a disturbance in the Force.

00:02:21:090000.Speaker: Leonard
00:02:21:090000.Dialogue: A bad feeling I have about this.

00:02:48:050000.Speaker: Leonard
00:02:48:050000.Dialogue: Dennis, how long have you been in America?

00:02:50:120000.Speaker: Leonard
00:02:50:120000.Dialogue: No kidding. You speak English really well.

00:02:55:190000.Speaker: Dennis
00:02:55:190000.Dialogue: Except for your tendency to end sentences with prepositions.

00:03:08:100000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:03:08:100000.Dialogue: All right... And this is my office.

00:03:10:170000.Speaker: Dennis
00:03:10:170000.Dialogue: Is this part of the tour?

00:03:14:010000.Speaker: Leonard
00:03:14:010000.Dialogue: Sheldon, we've hardly shown him anything.

00:03:16:110000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:03:16:110000.Dialogue: All right. This is my desk. These are my books; this is my door. Please close it behind you. Goodbye.

00:03:25:100000.Speaker: Dennis
00:03:25:100000.Dialogue: Looks like you're doing work in quantum loop corrections.

00:03:30:140000.Speaker: Dennis
00:03:30:140000.Dialogue: You see where you went wrong, don't you?

00:03:38:070000.Speaker: Leonard
00:03:38:070000.Dialogue: Come on. I'll show you the rec center. They've got Nautilus equipment.

00:03:41:180000.Speaker: Dennis
00:03:41:180000.Dialogue: Do I look like I lift weights?

00:03:47:060000.Speaker: Dennis
00:03:47:060000.Dialogue: It's startling you haven't considered a Lorentz invariant or field theory approach.

00:03:52:010000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:03:52:010000.Dialogue: You think I haven't considered it? You really think I haven't considered it?

00:04:06:180000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:04:06:180000.Dialogue: Yes. In fact, I am the youngest person ever to win it.

00:04:14:160000.Speaker: Dennis
00:04:14:160000.Dialogue: You were the youngest person ever to win it.

00:04:20:130000.Speaker: Leonard
00:04:20:130000.Dialogue: It's like looking into an obnoxious little mirror, isn't it?

00:04:28:070000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:04:28:070000.Speaker: Penny
00:04:28:070000.Dialogue: This is really delicious, isn't it?

00:04:34:040000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:04:34:040000.Speaker: Penny
00:04:34:040000.Dialogue: Still can't talk to me unless you're drunk, huh?

00:04:39:030000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:04:39:030000.Speaker: Penny

00:04:43:160000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:04:43:160000.Speaker: Howard

00:04:46:110000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:04:46:110000.Speaker: Howard
00:04:46:110000.Dialogue: How about a hug for Howie?

00:04:49:050000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:04:49:050000.Speaker: Penny

00:04:56:060000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:04:56:060000.Speaker: Leonard
00:04:56:060000.Dialogue: Something you'd like to share? A tale of woe, perhaps?

00:05:01:220000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:05:01:220000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:01:220000.Dialogue: 15 years old. Dennis Kim is 15 years old, and he's already correcting my work. Today, I went from being Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, to... You know, that other guy.

00:05:11:090000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:05:11:090000.Speaker: Howard

00:05:15:010000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:05:15:010000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:15:010000.Dialogue: Oh God, now even you are smarter than me.

00:05:18:190000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:05:18:190000.Speaker: Howard
00:05:18:190000.Dialogue: You know, you don't have so many friends that you can afford to start insulting them.

00:05:24:050000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:05:24:050000.Speaker: Leonard
00:05:24:050000.Dialogue: Just eat, Sheldon, you'll feel better.

00:05:26:070000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:05:26:070000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:26:070000.Dialogue: Why waste food? In Texas, when a cow goes dry, they don't keep feeding it, they just... take her out and shoot her between the eyes.

00:05:34:020000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:05:34:020000.Speaker: Penny
00:05:34:020000.Dialogue: I'm confused. Did Sheldon stop giving milk?

00:05:38:120000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:05:38:120000.Speaker: Leonard
00:05:38:120000.Dialogue: You can't let this kid get to you. You always knew that someday someone younger and smarter would come along.

00:05:44:030000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:05:44:030000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:44:030000.Dialogue: Yes, but I assumed I would've been dead hundreds of years and that there'd be an asterisk by his name because he'd be a cyborg.

00:05:51:220000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:05:51:220000.Speaker: Penny
00:05:51:220000.Dialogue: So you've got a little competition. I really don't see what the big deal is.

00:05:55:100000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:05:55:100000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:55:100000.Dialogue: Of course you don't. You've never excelled at anything.

00:06:00:130000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:06:00:130000.Speaker: Penny
00:06:00:130000.Dialogue: I don't understand exactly how did he get any friends in the first place?

00:06:05:010000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:06:05:010000.Speaker: Howard

00:06:08:180000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:06:08:180000.Speaker: Leonard
00:06:08:180000.Dialogue: What are you gonna do, just give up?

00:06:12:140000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:06:12:140000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:06:12:140000.Dialogue: It's what a rational person does when his entire life's work is invalidated by a postpubescent Asian wunderkind.

00:06:19:180000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:06:19:180000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:06:19:180000.Dialogue: He ceases his fruitless efforts, he donates his body to scientific research, and he waits to die.

00:06:27:220000.Scene: The living room of the apartment.
00:06:27:220000.Speaker: Penny
00:06:27:220000.Dialogue: I'm confused again. Is he waiting, or do we get to shoot him between the eyes?

00:06:37:110000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:06:37:110000.Dialogue: I've decided you're right. My career is not over.

00:06:41:200000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:06:41:200000.Dialogue: Since the arrival of Dennis Kim has rendered my research pointless, I just have to find something else to focus on.

00:06:48:110000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:06:48:110000.Dialogue: So I've decided. I'm going to collaborate with you.

00:06:55:230000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:06:55:230000.Dialogue: So what exactly is it you do?

00:06:59:000000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:06:59:000000.Dialogue: You chatter on about it all the time, but I've never really paid attention.

00:07:03:180000.Speaker: Leonard
00:07:03:180000.Dialogue: Right now, I'm designing an experiment to study the soft component of cosmic radiation at see level, but I really don't need any help.

00:07:12:120000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:07:12:120000.Dialogue: See, what's this here in the schematic? Is that a laser array?

00:07:27:140000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:07:27:140000.Dialogue: Pretty sure is not very scientific. Is this how you normally work? Just hunches and guesses and stuff?

00:07:35:030000.Speaker: Leonard
00:07:35:030000.Dialogue: I understand that you're going through a bit of a career cris, you're searching for some other area where you can feel valuable and productive, but I need to tell you something. I want you to listen carefully.

00:07:50:100000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:07:50:100000.Dialogue: If you're concerned about sharing credit with me, your name can go first... I'm going.

00:07:59:060000.Speaker: Howard
00:07:59:060000.Dialogue: It's a small, brown paper bag, Ma! I'm looking in it right now. Why would I make that up? There's no Ding Dong in it.

00:08:11:140000.Speaker: Howard
00:08:11:140000.Dialogue: How are two Ding Dongs tomorrow gonna help me today?

00:08:22:130000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:08:22:130000.Dialogue: Engineering. Where the noble semiskilled laborers execute the vision of those who think and dream.

00:08:34:020000.Speaker: Howard
00:08:34:020000.Dialogue: Sheldon, what are you doing here?

00:08:36:130000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:08:36:130000.Dialogue: I just came by to say hello.

00:08:38:140000.Speaker: Howard
00:08:38:140000.Dialogue: I've been in this lab for 3 years. You've never come by to say hello.

00:08:41:090000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:08:41:090000.Dialogue: Up until now, I've had better things to do.

00:08:45:090000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:08:45:090000.Dialogue: So, what are we making today?

00:08:47:080000.Speaker: Howard
00:08:47:080000.Dialogue: A small payload support structure for a European science experimental package that's going up on a space shuttle.

00:08:55:100000.Speaker: Howard
00:08:55:100000.Dialogue: When this is done, it will be attached to the payload bay, and the sensor apparatus will rest on it.

00:09:08:210000.Speaker: Howard
00:09:08:210000.Dialogue: No, you don't understand. During acceleration, it needs to stay perfectly level and provide... Yeah, it's a shelf.

00:09:15:190000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:09:15:190000.Dialogue: I notice you're using titanium. Did you give any consideration to carbon nanotubes? They're lighter, cheaper, and have twice the tensile strength.

00:09:24:080000.Speaker: Howard
00:09:24:080000.Dialogue: There's a diploma in my office that says I have a master's in engineering.

00:09:28:210000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:09:28:210000.Dialogue: You also have a note from your mother that says, I love you, Bubula.

00:09:34:220000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:09:34:220000.Dialogue: But neither of those is a cogent argument for titanium over nanotubes.

00:09:43:060000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:09:43:060000.Dialogue: Did Leonard tell you to say that?

00:09:45:110000.Speaker: Howard
00:09:45:110000.Dialogue: No, I thought of it all by myself.

00:09:50:010000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:09:50:010000.Dialogue: That can't be a coincidence. There must be some causal link I'm missing.

00:10:17:190000.Speaker: Raj
00:10:17:190000.Dialogue: Do you know what he did? He watched me work for 10 min, and then started to design a simple piece of software that could replace me.

00:10:30:230000.Speaker: Howard
00:10:30:230000.Dialogue: Something's got to be done about him.

00:10:33:000000.Speaker: Leonard
00:10:33:000000.Dialogue: Like what? He'll never be able to cope with the fact that some 15-year-old kid is smarter and more accomplished than he is.

00:10:39:150000.Speaker: Raj
00:10:39:150000.Dialogue: What if something happened to this boy so he was no longer a threat to Sheldon?

00:10:45:080000.Speaker: Howard
00:10:45:080000.Dialogue: Then our problem would be solved.

00:10:48:070000.Speaker: Leonard
00:10:48:070000.Dialogue: Hang on, are we talking about murdering Dennis Kim? I'm not saying no.

00:10:54:210000.Speaker: Howard
00:10:54:210000.Dialogue: We don't have to go that far. There are other means available.

00:10:58:050000.Speaker: Raj
00:10:58:050000.Dialogue: We can't send him back to North Korea. He knows how to get out.

00:11:04:140000.Speaker: Howard
00:11:04:140000.Dialogue: The only thing we need to do is make this Kim kid lose his focus.

00:11:07:230000.Speaker: Leonard
00:11:07:230000.Dialogue: Won't happen. He is not interested in anything but physics.

00:11:16:040000.Speaker: Howard
00:11:16:040000.Dialogue: The one thing that can completely derail a world-class mind.

00:11:20:200000.Speaker: Howard
00:11:20:200000.Dialogue: Yeah, so? When I was 15, I met Denise Palmeri and my grade point average fell from a 5.0 to a 1.8.

00:11:29:110000.Speaker: Howard
00:11:29:110000.Dialogue: No, I just... wasted a lot of time thinking about what it would be like if she did.

00:11:35:110000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:11:35:110000.Dialogue: Oh, good, you're all here. Look, if the three of you drop whatever it is you're working on and join me, we could lick cold fusion in less than a decade. 12 years, tops. Go away?

00:11:59:190000.Speaker: Howard
00:11:59:190000.Dialogue: We need a hot 15-year-old Asian girl with a thing for smart guys.

00:12:04:230000.Speaker: Leonard
00:12:04:230000.Dialogue: Howard, that's racist. Any 15-year-old girl will do the trick.

00:12:15:030000.Speaker: Raj
00:12:15:030000.Dialogue: It's possible she may have misunderstood us.

00:12:24:040000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:12:24:040000.Speaker: Gablehouser

00:12:26:080000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:12:26:080000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:12:26:080000.Dialogue: No, please come in. I think you'll appreciate this. This is very exciting.

00:12:30:120000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:12:30:120000.Speaker: Gablehouser

00:12:43:000000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:12:43:000000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:12:43:000000.Dialogue: I will solve the Middle East crisis by building an exact replica of Jerusalem in the middle of the Mexican desert.

00:12:50:090000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:12:50:090000.Speaker: Gablehouser

00:12:51:170000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:12:51:170000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:12:51:170000.Dialogue: It's like the baseball movie. Build it and they will come.

00:12:56:170000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:12:56:170000.Speaker: Gablehouser

00:12:58:020000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:12:58:020000.Speaker: Sheldon

00:13:00:040000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:13:00:040000.Speaker: Gablehouser

00:13:04:210000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:13:04:210000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:13:04:210000.Dialogue: Okay, well, speaking of spreads, we're having a small welcoming party this afternoon for Mr. Kim who's agreed to join us here at the university.

00:13:12:140000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:13:12:140000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:13:12:140000.Dialogue: Of course he has. The Oracle told us little Neo was the one.

00:13:19:070000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:13:19:070000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:13:19:070000.Dialogue: You can see the matrix, can't you?

00:13:22:060000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:13:22:060000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:13:22:060000.Dialogue: Well, obviously you're very busy with your... Come, Dennis. You'll have to excuse Dr. Cooper. He's been under a lot of... He's nuts.

00:13:41:050000.Scene: Sheldon’s office. He is making measurements on maps. There is a knock on the door.
00:13:41:050000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:13:41:050000.Dialogue: They'll come, they'll settle, and I'll win the prize.

00:13:46:090000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:13:46:090000.Dialogue: I really don't understand your objections, professor Goldfarb. Why wouldn't the Sonora desert make a perfectly good promised land?

00:13:56:140000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:13:56:140000.Dialogue: We could call it Nuevo Jerusalem.

00:14:06:050000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:14:06:050000.Dialogue: Why are all these young women here?

00:14:08:040000.Speaker: Leonard
00:14:08:040000.Dialogue: It's Take Your Daughter To Work Day.

00:14:10:160000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:14:10:160000.Dialogue: Really? I was not aware of that.

00:14:12:200000.Speaker: Raj
00:14:12:200000.Dialogue: Yes. There was a very official e-mail sent to everyone whose insurance files indicated they had daughters between the ages of 14 and 16.

00:14:25:110000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:14:25:110000.Dialogue: There's the man of the hour.

00:14:28:230000.Speaker: Leonard
00:14:28:230000.Dialogue: Okay, so we now have a socially-awkward genius in a room full of attractive, age-appropriate women.

00:14:33:220000.Speaker: Howard
00:14:33:220000.Dialogue: All he has to do now is hook up with one of them.

00:14:44:070000.Speaker: Leonard
00:14:44:070000.Dialogue: Anyone else see the flaw in this plan?

00:14:56:180000.Speaker: Howard
00:14:56:180000.Dialogue: I don't think you mean we can't. I think you mean we shouldn't.

00:15:01:000000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:15:01:000000.Dialogue: You're a Jew. If there was another Wailing Wall exactly like the one in Jerusalem but close to taco stands and cheap prescription drugs, would you still be able to wail at it? Okay, it's definitely me.

00:15:17:080000.Speaker: Leonard
00:15:17:080000.Dialogue: We cannot leave this to chance. Let's pick a girl and figure out how to get her together with Dennis.

00:15:25:130000.Speaker: Howard
00:15:25:130000.Dialogue: I know the type. Cheerleader, student council, goes out with the jocks, won't even look at anybody in the gifted program. If after 2 years of begging, she agrees to go out with you, it turns out to be a setup and you're in your mom's car with your pants off while the whole football team laughs at y...

00:15:50:150000.Speaker: Leonard
00:15:50:150000.Dialogue: Sure, if he wants to spend two years doing her homework while she drinks herself into a stupor with nonfat White Russians. You're holding her head out of the toilet while she's puking and telling you she wishes more guys were like you. Then she gets into Cornell because you wrote her essay for her and you drive up to visit her one weekend and she acts like she doesn't even know you.

00:16:16:060000.Speaker: Howard
00:16:16:060000.Dialogue: Interesting, kind of pretty, a little chubby, so probably low self-esteem.

00:16:20:050000.Speaker: Leonard
00:16:20:050000.Dialogue: I think that's our girl. One of us should go talk to her.

00:16:23:000000.Speaker: Raj
00:16:23:000000.Dialogue: I can't talk to her... you do it.

00:16:24:230000.Speaker: Leonard
00:16:24:230000.Dialogue: I can't just go up and talk to her. Howard, you talk to her.

00:16:29:090000.Speaker: Howard
00:16:29:090000.Dialogue: She'll never go for the kid once she gets a peek at this.

00:16:34:220000.Speaker: Raj
00:16:34:220000.Dialogue: In India, this would be simpler. 5 min with her dad, 20 goats and a laptop, and we'd be done.

00:16:55:050000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:16:55:050000.Dialogue: Could I have everyone's attention, please? What a wonderful occasion this is, and how fortunate that it should happen to fall on Take Your Daughter to Work Day.

00:17:06:110000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:17:06:110000.Dialogue: We're here to welcome Mr. Dennis Kim to our little family.

00:17:13:210000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:17:13:210000.Dialogue: Mr. Kim was not only the valedictorian at Stanford University, he is also the youngest recipient of the prestigious Stevenson Award.

00:17:23:070000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:17:23:070000.Dialogue: Youngest till the cyborgs rise up!

00:17:26:140000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:17:26:140000.Dialogue: And now, without any further ado, let me introduce the man of the hour, Mr. Dennis Kim.

00:17:41:080000.Speaker: Gablehouser
00:17:41:080000.Dialogue: Would you like to tell us a little bit about your upcoming research?

00:17:44:130000.Speaker: Dennis
00:17:44:130000.Dialogue: No, thanks. I'm going to the mall with Emma.

00:17:57:120000.Speaker: Howard
00:17:57:120000.Dialogue: Did anyone see how he did it?

00:18:03:140000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:18:03:140000.Dialogue: Ladies and gentlemen, honored daughters, while Mr. Kim, by virtue of his youth and naivete, has fallen prey to the inexplicable need for human contact, let me step in and assure you that my research will go on uninterrupted, and that social relationships will continue to baffle and repulse me.

00:18:30:090000.Speaker: Raj
00:18:30:090000.Dialogue: Forget the mission. How did that little yutz get a girl on his own?

00:18:34:060000.Speaker: Howard
00:18:34:060000.Dialogue: I guess times have changed since we were young. Smart is the new sexy.

00:18:39:140000.Speaker: Leonard
00:18:39:140000.Dialogue: Then why do we go home alone every night? We're still smart.

00:18:43:010000.Speaker: Raj
00:18:43:010000.Dialogue: Maybe we're too smart. So smart it's off-putting.

00:18:52:180000.Scene: The park. The four guys are carrying remote control rockets.
00:18:52:180000.Speaker: Howard
00:18:52:180000.Dialogue: Unbelievable. Components I built are on the International Space Station and I get a ticket for launching a model rocket in the park.
